fields.location: Furniture, room 133, case BY9, shelf LEDGE 2
fields.history_note:
Given by Lord Sanderson, G.C.B, K.C.M.G., I.S.O. (RF19/2664). O. Brackett recommended acceptance of the 'woodcarving tools to be framed for the use of students or possibly exhibited. But I hardly think they ought to be registered among our ordinary woodwork acquisitions, as they come under the heading of materials, not works of art etc.' (and subsequent discussion regarding an economical method of museum numbering).

Lord Sanderson noted in correspondence with the Museum that he had 'acquired them while learning the art [of wood carving] under Rogers', possibly WILLIAM GIBBS ROGERS (1792 - 1875) the eminent woodcarver and imitator of Grinling Gibbons. In 1850, W.G. Rogers was elected to the committee for carrying out the scheme of the Great Exhibition, and received a commission from Queen Victoria to carve a cradle in boxwood in the Italian style, which was exhibited and much admired at the exhibition in 1851.  The collection included one 'unfinished panel with design [a print showing the source] (My work was interrupted by appointment to some odious committee). Perhaps some student would like to complete it. I shall of course be highly honoured  if the tools or any portion of them are thought worthy of being made an exhibit. There are really enough for two people, as my sister also too lessons.'
